entry.title: [Private Network Access] Wait for permission result in preflight controller
entry.content:
`HandleResponseBody` won't wait for permission callback, will run the complete callback with NetError::ERR_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES and remove current preflight loader from the controller in `RemoveFromController`, which means the PNA preflight will always fails.



This CL attempt to solve the problem above and let the preflight loader wait for permission result legitimately.



See more: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Q18g4fZoDIYQ9IuxlZTaItgkzfiz_tCqaEAI8J3Y1WY/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: [ios] Replace webStateList:willDetachWebState:atIndex: and webStateList:willCloseWebState:atIndex:userAction: with willChangeWebStateList:change:selection:
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new WebStateListWillChange() API to notify a WebState will be changed to observers. WillDetachWebStateAt() and WillCloseWebStateAt() APIs are replaced by it.



This CL is a part of refactoring WebStateListObserver API:

Step 1 [Done]: Introduce WebStateListDidChange() and replace WebStateReplacedAt() with it

Step 2 [Done]: Replace WebStateInsertedAt() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 3 [Done]: Replace WebStateMoved() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 4 [Done]: Replace WebStateDetachedAt() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 5 [Now]: Introduce WebStateListWillChange() and Replace Will*() with it

Step 5-1: Introduce WillWebStateListChanged() and replace Will*() in the C++ side. (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4640748)

Step 5-2 [This CL]: Replace will*() in the Objective-C side.

Step 5-3: Simplify the API behavior. See the detail below. (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4650366)

Step 6: Migrate WebStateActivatedAt() and WebStatePinnedStateChanged() to WebStateListChanged()



The series of CLs in Step 5 will simplify the API behavior.

Currently, 3 APIs are called in total when a WebState is detached from WebStateList and destroyed:

1. WillDetachWebStateAt() is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. WillCloseWebStateAt() is called.

4. and then a WebState is destroyed.



After Step 5-3, 2 APIs will be called:

1. WebStateListWillChange() with kDetach is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. and then a WebState is destroyed.



See https://docs.google.com/document/d/1I1QUZAexM1eMI2l2oriZl5GARrtofNI0SxHUPB4h-YE/edit?usp=sharing for more details (internal document).

entry.title: Reland "[Re-land][Browsing Data Model][site data] Report storage accesses to BDM"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 4e8da3bf29612912556b4d37c35fbf6a974d164b



The revert was automated due to a conflict with crrev.com/c/4660415

which added more tests to cookie_controls_controller_unittest.cc and

was submitted 30 minutes prior to this change and trybots passed on both changes failing to capture this issue.



Original change's description:

> [Re-land][Browsing Data Model][site data] Report storage accesses to BDM

>

> This is a re-land change. There were some tests failing on crrev.com/c/4608424 due to 1p/3p context lost as we were recording metrics for storage access.

> It was wrong to assume that the context could be derived solely from the storage key and in this updated re-land change I've reverted this line to use the passed argument of `top_frame_origin`.

>

> In this CL:

> - Introduced `SessionStorage` type to BDM for access reports.

> - Moved storage handling under the new feature `kMigrateStorageToBDM`.

> - Updated storage access report to use `blink::StorageKey` instead of

> `GURL` to maintain 3p context and support storage partitioning.

> - Exposed storage_key() method to the RenderFrameHost public interface.

> - Reported access for storage types (i.e. local storage, session storage

> and quota managed storage) to BDM in site data.

> - Added browser tests for all new access reports in BDM.

> - WebSQL is covered in access reports and its browser test relating to

entry.title: Reorganize data removal for media device salts
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, the global salt was deleted as part of global cookie

deletion. This CL creates a new data type for salts, makes it part of DOM storage, and deletes salts as part of deletion of browsing data.

The global salt is still deleted on global cookie deletion to preserve

existing behavior.



This is in preparation for a new asynchronous per-storage-key backend

for salts and its integration with the UI for deleting browsing data per

origin/storage key. That UI specifies DATA_TYPE_DOM_STORAGE as remove mask.



Context: go/media-device-salt-partitioning

entry.title: Refactor transform updates for LayoutSVGContainer classes
entry.content:
Move the handling of the `needs_transform_update_` from the various

subclasses that support transforms to the base container class

(LayoutSVGContainer). This means that any side-effects on this flag

in the subclasses' CalculateLocalTransform() implementations can be

avoided.



This will help in supporting 'transform-box: stroke-box', since that box

can't be computed until after layout of any children has completed.

entry.title: [ios][web] Expose a method to clone a WebState
entry.content:
There are a few features that need to clone a WebState (e.g. prerender

or preview). The idea is to create a new tab with the same navigation

history, that can be used to replace an existing tab depending on the

user actions (e.g. navigating to the pre-rendered page).



Currently all client had to re-implement cloning as a serialisation

followed by a deserialisation, which will become difficult to perform

with the new serialisation code.



Expose a new method from WebState API will eventually allow to have

logic that is aware of the implementation of the serialisation and

that can optimise the operation.



Bug: 1291626, 1383087

entry.title: [siso] Implement clang_code_coverage_wrapper.py logic in Siso config
entry.content:
# Problem



GN can't generate different flags per compile action.

Coverage build uses clang_code_coverage_wrapper.py to strip coverage flags dynamically.



# Solution



This CL implements the same logic in Siso config for the following motivations:

- It can avoid process invocations. (clang_code_coverage_wrapper.py and rewrapper)

- Siso can run raw clang compile actions remotely without the coverage wrapper + instrument file. There is almost no chance to hit remote cache because the instrument file varies and is included in the cache key.



See b/278225415 for the details.



# Benchmark



```

❯ cat out/rbe-coverage/args.gn

use_remoteexec = true

use_clang_coverage = true

coverage_instrumentation_input_file = "//.code-coverage/files_to_instrument.txt"



❯ hyperfine --runs 5 --show-output --export-json coverage-build-bench.json \

--prepare "gn clean out/rbe-coverage" \

--command-name "Run code coverage wrappers with rewrapper" "autosiso -C out/rbe-coverage chrome" \

--prepare "gn clean out/rbe-coverage" \

--command-name "Strip code coverage wrappers by Siso config" "autosiso -config=rewrapper_to_reproxy -C out/rbe-coverage chrome"



Benchmark 1: Run code coverage wrappers with rewrapper

Time (mean ± σ): 180.876 s ± 68.124 s [User: 4331.966 s, System: 2582.852 s]

Range (min … max): 147.782 s … 302.670 s 5 runs



Benchmark 2: Strip code coverage wrappers by Siso config

Time (mean ± σ): 148.540 s ± 15.393 s [User: 3050.612 s, System: 447.749 s]

Range (min … max): 131.963 s … 172.993 s 5 runs



Summary

'Strip code coverage wrappers by Siso config' ran

1.22 ± 0.48 times faster than 'Run code coverage wrappers with rewrapper'

```



# Out of scope



This CL is tested only on Linux for now.

I will follow up benchmarking (and fix if necessary) in another CL.



Bug: b/289303148, b/278225415

entry.title: [a11y] Shrink AXPlatformNode by 8 bytes
entry.content:
AXPlatformNode::is_primary_web_contents_for_window_ was used on Linux to

find the "primary" web content document for the sake of relations. Since

this is only ever the case for a single node per browser window, it's

wasteful to track it via a member on every single accessible node. Track

this on BrowserAccessibilityManagerAuraLinux (one per RenderFrameHost)

henceforth.



To accomplish this, WebView now tells the primary node's delegate that

it is primary for the window. BrowserAccessibilityAuraLinux handles this

by notifying its BrowserAccessibilityManagerAuraLinux, which keeps track

of the primary. Likewise, AXPlatformNodeAuraLinux now asks a node's

delegate if it is the primary when computing relations.
